04176nam a22005415i 9780773551770DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735517707 a10.1515/97807735517702doi  a(DE-B1597)656895  a(OCoLC)981935176  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1010b.C36 2017 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a9712231 aCampbell, Claire Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNature, Place, and Story :bRethinking Historic Sites in Canada /cClaire Elizabeth Campbell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b10 photos, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Rural, Wildland, and Resource Studies ;v800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tHistoric Sites in Canada and the Place of Environmental History -- tGateway to a New World: L'Anse aux Meadows -- tIdyll and Industry: Grand Pré -- tWilderness, Lost and Found: Fort William -- tVariety, Heritage, Adventure, and Park: The Forks of the Red River -- tNature's Gentlemen and a Nation's Frontier: The Bar U Ranch -- tWhat Were We, and What Shall We Be? -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNational historic sites commemorate decisive moments in the making of Canada. But seen through an environmental lens, these sites become artifacts of a bigger story: the occupation and transformation of nature into nation. In an age of pressing discussions about environmental sustainability, there is a growing need to know more about the history of our relationship with the natural world and what lessons these places of public history, regional identity, and national narrative can teach us. Nature, Place, and Story provides new interpretations for five of Canada’s largest and most iconic historic sites (two of which are UNESCO World Heritage Sites): L’Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland; Grand Pré, Nova Scotia; Fort William, Ontario; the Forks of the Red River, Manitoba; and the Bar U Ranch, Alberta. At each location, Claire Campbell rewrites public history as environmental history, revealing the country’s debt to the power and fragility of the natural world, and the relevance of the past to understanding climate change, agricultural sustainability, wilderness protection, urban reclamation, and fossil fuel extraction. From the medieval Atlantic to modern ranchlands, environmental history speaks directly to contemporary questions about the health of Canada’s habitat. Bringing together public and environmental history in an entirely new way, Nature, Place, and Story is a lively and ambitious call for a fresh perspective on natural heritage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoric siteszCanada. 0aPublic historyzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355177040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773551770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773551770/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles